Airports rarely make for important news stories, aside from some sort of
aerial disaster or because personnel strikes turn them into a purgatory for
fliers. Spain, however, has an airport with its own star, which has made both
print and online headlines since its opening: [Castellón
airport](http://www.aerocas.com/?idioma=es) [es].

This airport was conceived, like so many other absurd public works, in the
last decade at the start of the economic crisis, and [was opened with
fanfare](http://www.publico.es/espana/368050/fabra-inaugura-en-castellon-un-
aeropuerto-sin-aviones) [es] by the then-president of the Council of
Castellón, Carlos Fabra, in March 2011, weeks before the municipal elections,
despite the fact that facility had no scheduled flights. In fact, they did not
even have an air navigation permit. 1500 people attended the event, including
Francisco Camps, President at the time of the Generalitat Valenciana, who left
office after being [charged with
bribery](http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2011/07/20/actualidad/1311149221_563723.html)
[es]. The opening had some borderline grotesque moments that were captured in
this fun video from [El Intermedio](http://www.lasexta.com/programas/el-
intermedio/) [es], La Sexta's abrasive program.

Adding to the list of nonsense that surrounds this airport is [an error in
construction](http://ccaa.elpais.com/ccaa/2012/02/14/valencia/1329253727_378240.html)
[es] that disables

the runway and landing strips and forces them to fix it before it is even
debuted, in addition to the [construction of a hideously monumental
sculpture](http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2012/09/18/valencia/1347994652.html)
[es] — an homage to Fabra, according to its artist — in the access roundabout,
which has cost 300,000 euros and has not withstood the humidity of the area.

[![Castellón Airport.](https://globalvoicesonline.org/wp-
content/uploads/2013/01/Aeropuerto-de-
Castellón-375x229.jpg)](http://blogs.ideal.es/la-campana-de-la-
vela/2012/07/17/el-aeropuerto-fantasma/)

Castellón Airport. From the Blog #La Campana De La Vela.

The airport, although not operational, has considerable annual costs, as [this
article from elplural.com](http://www.elplural.com/2012/09/04/el-director-del-
aeropuerto-de-castellon-se-subio-el-sueldo-4-000-euros-en-2010/) [es] breaks
down:

[![Manchas de óxido en la estatua que preside la entrada al aeropuerto. Foto
del blog Hits Book.](https://es.globalvoicesonline.org/wp-
content/uploads/2013/01/oxido-240x300.jpg)](http://www.hitsbook.com/blog/2012/09/300-000-euros-
del-erario-publico-para-generar-oxido/)

Oxidized stains on the statue that presides over the entrance to the airport.
Photo from blog Hits Book.

> Juan García Salas, director general de
> [Aerocas](http://www.preferente.com/noticias-de-
> transportes/aeropuertos/carlos-fabra-ratificado-como-presidente-de-
> aerocas-85759.html) [la sociedad pública que gestiona el aeropuerto], cobró
> en 2011 88.104 euros, una cantidad bastante superior a los 84.200 euros
> brutos que ganó en 2010. (…)
>
> Todavía hay más. Los gastos de explotación del aeropuerto de Castellón
> ascendieron en 2011 a un total de 6.484.935 euros. De ese total,
> 5.092.596,22 euros se gastaron en el apartado de publicidad, propaganda y
> relaciones públicas; es decir, más del 78%. Del resto, 918.663 euros fueron
> a parar a servicios profesionales independientes; 368.865,49 euros a los
> salarios de sus siete trabajadores; 223.074 euros a trabajos realizados por
> otras empresas; 129.430 a otros servicios; 23.412 a arrendamientos y cánones
> y 23.006 a servicios bancarios o similares, entre otros apuntes.

> Juan García Salas, General Director of Aerocas [the public society that
> manages the airport], charged 88,104 euros in 2011, a quantity significantly
> higher than the 84,200 euros they grossed in 2010. (…)
>
> There's still more. Castellón airport's operating costs amounted to a total
> of 6,484,935 euros in 2011. Of this total amount, 5,092,596.22 euros were
> spent on a portion of publicity, propaganda, and public relations; that is
> to say, more than 78%. Of the remainder, 918,663 euros went to independent
> professional services: 368,865.49 euros to the salaries of its seven
> employees; 223,074 euros work done by other companies; 129,430 to other
> services; 23,412 to leases and royalties and 23,006 to bank services or
> something similar, among other calculations.

[Carlos Fabra](http://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlos_Fabra_Carreras) [es], the
main promoter of this airport and a People's Party politician, belongs to a
family with a long political legacy in Castellón. He was council president of
this province from 1995 to 2011, a post he left after being charged with
crimes of bribery and influence peddling in 2010. He is also the father of
Andrea Fabra, the PP deputy that became infamous a few months ago for [yelling
“Fuck them!” at the Congress](https://globalvoicesonline.org/2012/07/15/spain-
parliamentarian-insults-millions-of-unemployed-people/) while President Rajoy
announced new cuts to unemployment benefits.

A few days ago, Fabra himself, now that he presides over Aerocas, announced
that a venture capital business group has made an offer to [purchase Castellón
airport](http://www.lasprovincias.es/20130109/comunitatvalenciana/castellon/aeropuerto-
castellon-vendido-201301091525.html) [es] for 200 million euros. The
operation, although it is [not nearly as
beneficial](http://vozpopuli.com/empresas/19726-fabra-quiere-regalar-el-
aeropuerto-de-castellon-el-precio-apenas-cubre-la-deuda) [es] as the Aerocas
managers make it out to be, is still good news, given that its maintenance
costs. Nevertheless, the news has surprised many people, since apparently the
airport is a completely useless infrastructure, and it is worth wondering why
anyone would want to take it on.

As such, Twitter created the hashtag [#
**NuevosUsosAeropuertoDeCastellón**](https://twitter.com/search/realtime?q=%23nuevosusosaeropuertodecastell%C3%B3n&src=hash)
[es] (#NewUsesCastellónAirport), which became a trending topic on January 10,
and netizens began coming up with very innovative ideas.

